{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 04:36:59.549353", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of Network Health\n- Overall OSPF core and most distribution/host subnets are healthy: hosts in 10.1.0.0/16 and 10.2.2.0/24, 10.2.3.0/24, 10.2.4.0/24 exhibit normal reachability and latency to peers and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24). DNS resolution and HTTP access via the load balancer (web99.local) are normal from 10.1.x hosts.\n- One access segment, 10.2.1.0/24, is abnormal: hosts do not have IP addresses and are effectively isolated.\n\nDetected Anomalies\n- DHCP failure and host isolation on 10.2.1.0/24:\n  - get_reachability shows every host in 10.2.1.0/24 with status “unknown,” unlike other 10.2.x subnets which succeed.\n  - host_2_1_1_1 network config shows no IPv4 address on eth0 (UP but no inet), indicating DHCP did not succeed.\n- Router_dist_2_1 OSPF isolation:\n  - Router router_dist_2_1 has OSPF configured under area 66 and reports “Number of fully adjacent neighbors: 0.”\n  - Its routing table contains only connected routes (10.2.1.0/24 on br0 and 172.16.0.14/31 on eth0), with no routes toward the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) or the rest of the network.\n  - Pings from router_dist_2_1 to the DHCP server (10.200.0.8) and to upstream peer by name fail with “Network is unreachable,” consistent with missing OSPF-learned routes.\n- OSPF topology elsewhere is healthy:\n  - router_core_2 is ABR with neighbors fully adjacent on multiple core and distribution links; it learns 10.200.0.0/24 and other distribution subnets normally.\n  - Most hosts and servers have normal inter-area reachability and acceptable latency.\n\nFault Localization\n- Fault domain: Distribution block for core 2, specifically the 10.2.1.0/24 segment.\n- Faulty device: router_dist_2_1 (distribution router for 10.2.1.0/24).\n  - L2 to access is fine (host NIC up, switch link implied). The failure is at L3: router_dist_2_1 is not participating in the OSPF domain correctly and therefore cannot relay DHCP unicast to the DHCP server or route traffic off the segment.\n\nRoot Cause Analysis\n- Misconfigured OSPF area on router_dist_2_1 isolates it from the OSPF domain:\n  - router_dist_2_1 OSPF configuration:\n    - “network 10.2.1.0/24 area 66”\n    - “network 172.16.0.14/31 area 66”\n    - OSPF shows 0 fully adjacent neighbors.\n  - The core uses area 0.0.0.1 for distribution adjacencies; router_core_2 has active neighbors on the 172.16.0.x links for other distribution routers but not with 172.16.0.15 (router_dist_2_1).\n  - Area mismatch (area 66 vs area 0.0.0.1) prevents OSPF adjacency formation between router_dist_2_1 and the core, leaving router_dist_2_1 with only connected routes.\n- Consequence path:\n  - No OSPF adjacency → no route from 10.2.1.0/24 to 10.200.0.0/24 → DHCP relay unicast packets can’t reach the central DHCP server → hosts on 10.2.1.0/24 don’t obtain leases and remain without IPs → entire 10.2.1.0/24 segment is effectively down.\n\nEvidence Highlights\n- host_2_1_1_1 net config:\n  - eth0 UP, no “inet” address; ip route empty.\n- router_dist_2_1:\n  - FRR OSPF: area 66, “Number of fully adjacent neighbors: 0”.\n  - Routes: only 10.2.1.0/24 (br0) and 172.16.0.14/31 (eth0) connected; nothing for 10.200.0.0/24.\n  - Ping to 10.200.0.2/10.200.0.8: “Network is unreachable.”\n- router_core_2:\n  - ABR with fully adjacent neighbors in backbone and area 0.0.0.1; normal routes to other 10.2.x subnets and 10.200.0.0/24.\n\nAdditional Observations\n- router_core_2 shows an OSPF route to 10.2.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.0/31 (likely via another core). This may be a byproduct of summarization/redistribution elsewhere and could cause a blackhole for inbound traffic destined to 10.2.1.0/24 while that segment is actually isolated. It does not change the primary diagnosis above.\n\nImpact Assessment\n- All hosts in 10.2.1.0/24 are unable to obtain IP addresses via DHCP and cannot reach any services.\n- Other subnets and services (DNS, web servers, load balancer) are unaffected and operating normally.\n\nConclusion\n- Anomaly detected: Yes — complete outage of 10.2.1.0/24 host subnet.\n- Localization: router_dist_2_1 (distribution router for 10.2.1.0/24).\n- Root cause: OSPF area mismatch on router_dist_2_1 (configured in area 66 instead of the distribution area used by the core), preventing adjacency and routing to the DHCP/server networks, resulting in DHCP failure and host isolation on 10.2.1.0/24.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 38064, "output_tokens": 5532, "total_tokens": 43596, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 37248}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4224}}}
